text:
one of the most powerful, difficult, and empowering books iâ€™ve ever read. i want to thank @rosemcgowan for her strength and bravery in telling her truths. the work that she has done, and continues to do, is giving strength to others and saving lives. unfortunately, i found her stories all too relatable, and i have many friends with similar stores too. this should not be. society: do better. i think this book is incredibly important for everyone, male or female, to read. trigger warning: there are graphic descriptions of assaults she endured, which are incredibly difficult to get through as a reader. even so, this book is full of so many valid thoughts and points. so many things brought to light. it is honest and brutal and unapologetic, which again, is important. her blunt unapologetic authenticity makes a lot of people uncomfortable, and we have to ask ourselves why that is. weâ€™ve been conditioned to be polite at all times, and to quietly endure horrific atrocities and keep it to ourselves in order to not upset anyone else or make anyone else uncomfortable with our truths. that needs to stop. we need to get used to hearing each otherâ€™s truths, even if they make us uncomfortable, instead of staying quiet and staying complacent, and allowing these horrible things to go unaddressed. itâ€™s important for the victims to be able to heal. it is important for the people who commit these terrible acts to be called out and shown for what they are. it is important for society to stop allowing these terrible things to happen, to be the norm. iâ€™m a proud member of rose army. this incredible woman, along with every victim around the world throughout history, have my support. 
this book is definitely not for the faint of heart, but thatâ€™s exactly why i think the faint of heart need to read it. walk a mile in this womanâ€™s shoes, because she represents so many more women than just herself. i really hope that i can someday meet her, shake her hand, and look her in the eye as i thank her in person. 
#rosearmy #equality #justice #timesup #metoo #book #books #feminist #brave #strength

text: i called a lot of people i grew up with recently. foster mom, out there being amazing, reminding me, as the only person who has respect and authority too, 'be good'. also with that in mind; we are the miller's.  today's discussion is about i don't know you, i don't your problems, and being blamed for whatever reason, as disoriented and just who the fuck are you as i am. you're adults and can't force blame of whatever the fuck in my direction constantly. or anyone, whether race, gender, seriously. a thing that happened when i moved, i have friends real and not so great, some started having kids, those new parents, not adjusting well, reverted back to blaming me for their shit. and some started to weirdly parent as my peers. roar. it took twenty years to realise, and then some still don't even see it. here, we are adults and i have no idea, what it is other than not being and entitled, that puts a target, to be thrown all the blame and disposed of. not a scape goat. a human, accountability regardless of where the system is headed needs to personally accounted for. i know my mistakes, you don't add yours to them. then it got me thinking of the kids at the border, when they join society, how nothing's their fault, and hopefully those future kids, do what's necessary to include them without purposely being destructive to their humanity. also in a phase im working through. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors

text:
for the past four months, @nadiamunla and i have been researching, conversing, diving deep and unpacking some huge topics behind the scenes.

it all started with the question....what now?

neither of us believe that the future is solely female. we believe the future is human.

we believe that if one side loses, we all lose. so given all that has happened over the last few years and the incredible uprise of the #metoo movement, we want to know...how can we trust our men again?

how can we put away the finger pointing and "witch hunting" and come together to support one another?

how do we bring men and women together in a safe space to open, share and heal?

introducing....âœ¨trusting our men againâœ¨

an interview series with 11 incredible men who have bravely stepped into the spotlight to talk about all things consent, #metoo, rape culture, nonverbal communication, polarity and so much more.

sign up by going here: http://trustingourmen.com

we begin jan 30!!!
.
.
.

a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

text:
i've heard about childhood explorations with friends (and even similar-aged cousins) from several women in my podcast interviews. children are naturally curious about sex and their bodies. but when they get caught, adults often shame them for it - and kids are left wondering why. 
#
i think it's because adults see the explorations through the lens of having become post-pubescent sexual beings, while the kids still see things through the lens of childhood explorations. it's hard for parents/adults to remember back to that time of innocent exploration - especially during this time of heightened awareness around molestation, exploitation, and #metoo.
#
i'm curious to know if this theory holds water - did you ever play "doctor" or "i'll show you mine if you show me yours" with a friend? do you look back on that as innocent fun or fraught with sexual tension?
#
listen to the good girls talk about sex podcast on your favorite podcast provider! link to podcast in bio. 
#

text:
a 17-year-old girl was raped in an alley way by a 27-year-old man in ireland. she wore a thong with a lace front the night she met with the man and the defense lawyer claimed she indicated consent by the way she was dressed. her rapist was charged not guilty and walked away with a clean slate. this case quickly brought hundreds of men and women in ireland to protest this case and women shared their underwear online with #thisisnotconsent

i march for the survivors of sexual violence who didnâ€™t have a voice for themselves and felt betrayed by their justice system when they were forced to relive the horrors of their sexual assault. as a society, we must do better in supporting our survivors by ending victim shaming. victim shaming easily forces the survivor to feel marginalized, not report the abuse, and blame themselves for being raped or assaulted. instead, we should listen and believe our survivors. provide them with resources to allow them to heal, encourage the survivor to get support, and be patient with them. 
to our survivor, we believe you and love you. you are heard and we will stand by you with unconditional love and support. there are people out there who are here to help youğŸ’–

check out this link if you need help or know someone who has been sexually assaulted. rainn.org or call 1-800-656-4673 (national sexual assault hotline)

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
dear friends,

we need your help.

we are facing uncertain times as the federal government shutdown continues with no immediate end in sight. dove center is calling on the community to stand with survivors to help ensure that the critical services on which they rely will continue without interruption.

the office on violence against women (ovw) and office for victims of crime (ovc) are set to close at 6 a.m. on friday, january 18th. this will be devastating for survivors and victim service agencies like dove as access to funding for critical needs and life-saving services will be cut off. survivors will face greater risks for homelessness and harm; and dove will face a resulting funding gap.

the shutdown will directly impact victim advocacy in the emergency room and courts; support groups and counseling; and access to trauma-informed training for advocates on the front line. it will interrupt our ability to provide housing support to some of the most vulnerable survivors. and because dove utilizes a broad network of partners to deliver these programs, the shutdown has the potential of far-reaching implications throughout our network.

as we anxiously wait for the government to reopen, we are asking you, dear friends and loyal supporters of dove, to help ensure there is no funding gap and local survivors receive timely assistance that is fundamental to their safety and healing.

as you consider ways to make a difference in our community for those impacted by the shutdown, please consider a gift to dove. your support means life-saving services remain accessible and reliable. even in this time of uncertainty. please give today at the link in our bio. 
in gratitude,
lindsey boyer, executive director at dove center

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
after weeks of putting this off due to fear and anxiety, iâ€™ve decided to finally make my first post as @my.reclamation. â €
â €
i created @my.reclamation because i amâ €
a two-time rape survivor and have struggled with the fallout associated with each rape. it can be extremely lonely. it can be dangerous to handle the thoughts and feelings post-trauma all alone. at times i wasnâ€™t sure if iâ€™d make it out alive. â €
â €
this is a reclamation of my mind, my passions, my body, my spirit... a reclamation of all the time i lost and all that was stolen from me. and hopefully, in some variant of a redemption arc, a reclamation of peace. â €
â €
@my.reclamation is to serve as many things for myself, and hopefully will help others along the way. i wanted an anonymous outlet for me to journal, vent â€” sometimes with specific ideas in mind, others that border on word vomiting with little-to-no direction. sometimes itâ€™s hard to do this to our friends or other people we care about in our â€œrealâ€ lives â€” it may be dangerous for us, or it can be intensive emotional labor for them. this is for me to unearth my thoughts into reality, with no strings attached. maybe you will find comfort or commonality in my posts, too. â €
â €
i want to be here to document the things that are helping me. i want to share and discuss things happening around us in the world. i want to share resources and tools. i want this to be a creative outlet. but more than anything i want this to aid in my healing and my peace, and maybe, eventually, freedom from the burden of these traumas. youâ€™ll see a bit of everything. and i hope it benefits you, too. â €
â €
iâ€™m unsure if there is a rape survivor or ptsd community here on instagram, but if there is i hope to find it and take part in it. â €
â €
thank you for reading this, and i hope to share more of myself and my journey with you in the near future. in the meantime, be gentle to yourself. iâ€™ll try to be gentle to myself, too ğŸ˜Œâ €
â €
(please be patient while i get into the swing of this and learn how to best run and organize this account!)â €
â €
#rapesurvivor #metoo #sexualassault #speakup #endthesilence #mentalhealth #rapeculture #healing #trauma

when i started @periodmovement my goal wasnâ€™t to make history, get involved in politics, or even grow the efforts nationally/globally. my co-founder, vincent, and i, were simply two 16-year-olds trying to distribute period products to homeless women in downtown portland, or. within a few months, sort of accidentally, we had chapters in multiple states bringing our mission to life in their own communities â€” and fast forward 4 years, we now have over 260 chapters worldwide and are gearing up for our second global conference this saturday - #periodcon
.
i never saw myself (and still donâ€™t) as someone who is making history â€” iâ€™m just doing what i love and fighting for a cause i truly believe in. that being said, running period has taught me to dream big â€” our mission is no longer just about product distribution, but is also about changing culture around menstruation and natural needs, and enacting period policies that will ensure access to menstrual hygiene for all. do we/i want to make history? yes â€” because menstrual hygiene is a right, and not a privilege, and itâ€™s about time we nationally repeal the #tampontax ğŸ‘ŠğŸ½
.
@jameelajamilofficial reposted this pic (swipe left) of @carolinegedwards today, with her #womensmarch sign that named me as a woman making historyâ€¦ and i was honestly shook, honored, and humbled to see my name next to some of my greatest sheroes. it really made me think though, because i donâ€™t always think of myself as making history, and it isnâ€™t one of my conscious goals to eitherâ€¦ i just think about doing everything i can to advance this #menstrualmovement â€” but @caroinegedwards , youâ€™re making me think that moving into 2019 and 2020, i need to adopt the mindset that we will be loud, and unapologetic, and ready to make some history!!!

text:
police began investigating the claims made against chris brown.

chris brown might have to face a french court in the future after a woman claimed the singer raped her in france. according to french tabloid publication closer, breezy is under investigation in france for allegedly raping a woman earlier this month.

a 24-year-old woman claims chris brown raped her on the night of jan. 15-16th after meeting at a nightclub in france. the woman filed a complaint to the police claiming that brown invited her to his hotel room at le mandarin oriental along with another woman. however, in her testimony, she claims that she ended up in a single room with chris brown where she claims she was raped.

she also alleges that breezyâ€™s bodyguard and his friend also abused her. paris parquet already opened a case and began investigating into the claims that he raped her at his hotel.

brown has yet to release a statement on the allegations.

brown has another sexual assault-related lawsuit to tend to in north america. the singer was sued for an alleged sexual assault committed by brownâ€™s friend at the â€œundecidedâ€ singerâ€™s mansion. while brown himself isnâ€™t accused of sexual assault, the woman claimed he provided cocaine, molly and other drugs to the guests.

brown has maintained his innocence and demanded that the judge throw away the case. get the full details at www.itskenbarbie.com what do you guys think? #chrisbrown #chrisbrownbreezy #chrisbrownofficial #chrisbrownconcert #breezy #chrisbreezy #undecided #undecidedchallenge #metoo #entertainment #entertainmentnews #entertainmentblog #gossip

text: today was a big day - the law society standards committee released its first decision about a sexual harassment complaint. my t-shirt from the lovely ladies at @nopesistersclothing summarises my thoughts. ğŸ‘some of my comments are below that will be in the media tomorrow. what do you guys think? ğŸ¤¨ the standards committee had to decide whether the partnerâ€™s conduct amounted to the statutory definition of unsatisfactory conduct or misconduct, the latter being more serious. to decide this they appear to have asked themselves: would lawyers of good standing simply find the conduct unacceptable or would they find it disgraceful or dishonourable. in relation to the second complainant, the partner non-consensually pinched the complainantâ€™s backside twice leaving a bruise and then later in the evening grabbed her wrist and forcibly squeezed her hand against his groin while saying â€œthis is for youâ€. the committee decided that lawyers of good standing would merely find this unacceptable, not disgraceful or dishonourable. i have serious concerns about this decision because on the face of it, what he did could amount to indecent assault under the crimes act which carries a maximum term of 7 years in prison. what he did is clearly disgraceful or dishonourable and it begs the worrying question, what more dreadful things does a lawyer have to do to meet the standards committee's misconduct threshold? ğŸ¤” in this case the penalty does not reflect the seriousness of what happened or act as a sufficient deterrent to others. in the very least he should have been suspended from practicing for an appropriate period of time â€“ the loss in income would have been a more appropriate penalty than a mere $12,500 fine. if he has been in a large firm on a big salary this will be a drop in the bucket for him. #metoo #lawyers #accountability #newzealand

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
tw: rape, sexual abuse/violence 
vii. on survival.

writing this piece pulled sunken parts of me to the surface, nearly sending me into a state of emergency.  as i relived this trauma, i celebrate the resilience that towers over it today. 
this shame is not mine, but his!  it is simply my truth. and as the author of my fate, i decide how this story ends. 
stronger than yesterday, i set fire to the narrative that survivors should stay silent.  instead, i will use my voice to scream until i break the stigma of rape that tries to minimize it as abuse.  i am here to obliterate the taboo of male rape.

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
footage of nigel farage swigging a pint and thanking steve bannon and breitbart for the brexit result was deleted from a breitbart youtube channel, following the data scandal surrounding cambridge analytica.
.
- well done bannon, well done breitbart, the ex-ukip leader announces in the short clip. - you helped with this. hugely.

farageâ€™s nod to steve bannon certainly hasnâ€™t aged well in the context of the recent storm around cambridge analyticaâ€™s influence over the eu referendum.

it was revealed that data from 50 million facebook profiles were looked at against the electoral register, and then used to build an algorithm which analyses peopleâ€™s personality traits in relation to their voting behaviour.

this data could then be used to find potential swing voters and create messages tailored to influence them politically.

the firmâ€™s vice president at the time was steve bannon, who was also head of the right-wing website breitbart and was running donald trumpâ€™s campaign to become us president.

self love is a journey that we travel on and we pick up tools along the way to create that self love, don't allow anyone or anything have power of you as you create your own self to be free.... this has been a journey for me as well i don't allow anyone to effect me , there negativity non loving relationship is there's not mine and i have chosen to remove that drama out of my life and only be surrounded in love for me and have used lots of amazing things to create that self love.... find your happy place.

think of a place that makes it simple to just be. that means being able to sit quietly and embrace the here and now. not thinking about what's going on at work or what bills need to be paid, you owe this happy place to yourself. self-love is all about connecting with yourself, and one of the easiest places to do that is in your happy place.

if you need help with direction contact me let me coach you to where you need to be 
#anjuahluwalia

text:
this post is dedicated to aiia maasarwe and to women all over the world who have lost their lives to violence by a man. i am survivor of multiple rapes, countless sexual assaults, harassment, sexism and violence from men. it crushes me knowing how many people can say their version of these things. trauma is not remembered as an orderly narrative, it can return as hallucinations, flashbacks of fragmented memories, images, sounds, body sensations and feelings of discomfort. my trauma and these sensations are always present, they even followed me to scotland. throughout this artist residency my psychosis jumped from being auditory, to being complete sensory hallucinations that seemed real. one example is that a man would attack me in my bed most nights, so it seemed, and each experience took a long time to recover, at least enough to delay carving marble. the trauma along with an increase in symptoms to a few chronic illnesses i have meant making the difficult decision to leave this work for now. the work was to accompany a film which focuses on funerary rituals of the area and a story in local folklore of a woman who became famous in death after she died by suicide in the 1700s. i had begun a mindful unveiling of this woman; barbara, her face protected by plaid. i relate to the story of barbara mcintosh and will share it alongside documentation of the film.
if you can, please read this recent article â€˜men of australia, it's time to pick your sideâ€™, written by clementine ford. published in the age on 17 january 2019
-
if any details i share of this work now or in the future are upsetting or triggering in any way please let me know and please contact any of these numbers if you or anyone you know needs to.â €

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

#metoo. raise your hands if someone else has been managing your money for you?
.
just because theyâ€™ve been doing it for you all this while doesnâ€™t mean it needs to be this way always. youâ€™ve earned every penny and now itâ€™s time to manage it yourself, gradually taking full control of your own finances. .
but before you do that learn the basics about money, brush up on your budgeting skills, ask questions, seek advice, and be confident.
.
since a lot of money related matters are largely dependent on power and expertise, if someone thinks youâ€™re incapable of managing it yourself it is easier for them to take control. but once youâ€™ve proved that you can handle your money, theyâ€™ll have confidence in you. theyâ€™ll trust you and it will be easier for them to hand over the reins to you.
.
of course, this wonâ€™t happen overnight and it will take some time.
.
so be patient. and remember during the process, it is completely okay to seek help, after all money is precious.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i burnt the things you gave me and i cleansed all of my surroundings. i have cried, cut and questioned myself. what did i do to feel this way? the highs and the lows take its toll. my brain doesnâ€™t agree with my existence. i blame you sometimes, and blame myself for ever loving you. i gave you my trust and you crushed it between your fingers when you touched my innocence. you talked a big game when it came to love, but you hurt me just the same as the ones before. talking about it makes my chest heavy, writing about it makes my hands tremble. people called me crazy for the way i was when i was with you. they looked at you in awe, but only i knew what true horrors laid in your intentions. you said you loved me, rescued me in ways i couldnâ€™t. your words made me believe you, but i shouldâ€™ve questioned your actions. -kavya baburaj
.
.
.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: i honestly canâ€™t believe iâ€™m posting this. i never thought i would and iâ€™m slightly panicking . today has been one of the hardest days of my life. so as some people know i try to post often and i only post photos that i love and feel really good in.... perfect hair. perfect make up. but not today. iâ€™m not posting this photo for attention for me. iâ€™m posting this message for attention for everyone men. woman and children. today i sat in a court room with a man who sexually assaulted me back in november. not many people know about this. and if you do know who it was please respect me by keeping it to yourself. there is more court dates to come and times where i will have to see this person. after seeing him today i have been crying for hours. mentally and emotionally exhausted and physically been ill. but i am so freaking proud of myself for standing up for what i know is right. it is never ever okay to put up with sexual assault from anyone. even if they are a partner. friend. family. ex partner. a stranger. it is never okay for someone to disrespect you like that. so if i can stand up and say #metoo then so can you! this photo is no makeup. messy natural hair. no pose or cheesy smile. this is me. this is real time. and this photo is of a strong woman who stands up for herself ! this photo of for all of you men woman and children who have been hurt. i believe you. and i stand with you #itsneverokay #standup

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

nel 1998 io avevo sei anni. in quel periodo il mio unico compito era imparare, e quello che mi veniva insegnato era, ai miei occhi, autorevole e incontrovertibile: mai avrei considerato plausibile un'alternativa, un modo diverso di contare, di mettere le virgole, di usare i verbi.
in quello stesso anno il @washingtonpost accendeva i riflettori su uno degli scandali piÃ¹ grossi della recente storia americana: il #sexgate. inutile dirvi cosa mi fu insegnato, in quella occasione. e che fatica, che impegno decennale mi ci volle per disimparare. 
autorevole e incontrovertibile, appunto, tanto che coi danni provocati da quella cultura ci facciamo i conti ancora oggi, nell'epoca del #metoo. sono nei discorsi che intercettiamo al bar, nei post su facebook, nei commenti avvelenati sotto gli articoli dei giornali online; ma noi ce la stiamo mettendo tutta, e continueremo a disimparare ogni giorno. 
oggi su uonnabi un esempio di chi ha disimparato perfettamente, di chi ora Ã¨ pulito e disintossicato.

text:
step 4 of our #16stepprogram - on how boys and men can step up and take action for #metoo.

talk to your sons, brothers, nephews and younger friends

cis-hetero men and their relationships with other men and boys are often infected with a lack of emotional openness. this is your time to start talking to your sons, your younger brothers, nephews, friends, cousins and colleagues. take the lead with having difficult conversations around gender discrimination, sexual assault, coercion, consent, masculinities, and sexualities and link it back to personal experiences and behaviours. understand that you control your own circle of influence and that you can create an impact on younger or more impressionable men and boys around you.

in collaboration with @thepixelproject .

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
the habits have been tough these past few weeks. it's easy to get swept in the waves of life and let impulsivity take you away.

or you can deliberately acknowledge what needs to be changed and create healthy habits and safe routines. 
just don't judge yourself and be so self-critical. you are doing the best you can. and that's fine.

that's what my little self would tell me and i would tell my little self.

#justdoit
#metoo
#calm

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
dear partners of sundance film festival, 
as you're probably aware, many people have been messaging you, asking you to cancel your sponsorship of sundance and sending you a petition that asks the festival to cancel screenings of a film concerning the singer in question. they are also boycotting your brands, products & services and some are even referring to sundance as 'the racist sundance festival.' their petition has now been signed by ~48,500 (a number equal to nearly half of the total sundance attendees): change.org/p/robert-redford-end-the-defamation-of-michael-jackson 
informing you of this development is important for four reasons... impact on revenue 
imagine that for every registered complaint (48,200), 50 others are also thinking the same. now imagine that each fan on the petition is worth only $2. do the math: 48,200 x 50 x $2 = $4,820,000 dollars. almost $5m dollars instantly lost by each company. the real number is orders of magnitude larger. this is what you actually stand to lose, as well as irreversible damage to your reputations. simply revoking your sponsorship of sundance can stop this. 
racism, fake news and #metoo 
sundance is digging up a dead black icon only to lynch him again. 
sundance has recently begged you speak to them first before you disassociate from the festival or message fans. isn't this really saying something? this 'documentary,' "leaving neverland," perpetuates racist myths (in origin) about one of the world's greatest black icons. the racist us media of the 1990s & 2000s (which has changed dramatically only in the last few years) encouraged this lie from the start and it's shocking to see sundance regurgitate it with a film featuring two disgruntled & denounced former business associates of this singer - the late michael jackson. 
this easily discredited documentary will also cause more fake news to proliferate with long-lasting residual power online, strengthening and emboldening a key component of the unfortunate political climate of today - a problem that individuals and corporations are desperately trying to solve. 
#sundance #sundancefilmfestival #stopleavingneverlandnow#innocent#stopleavingneverlandnow##justiceformj

text:
link in bio to the second of a two part interview i wrote a few weeks ago for adventurer and writer olivia round.Â Â @roundolivia this article explores the relationship between gender and violence for solo female travelers, and offers my basic perspective on risk management. .

i've traveled thousands of miles around the world by foot, bike, and thumb, a good chunk of that alone.Â  but of course never really aloneâ€”embedded in a world full of people, and all the things people are and do.Â  along the way i've experienced extraordinary human kindness, generosity, and connection.Â  i have been helped and cared for, by people from all walks of life, in all of the most humbling and heart-lifting ways.  i've also experienced persistant and undeniable male agression, in many forms. .

people frequently ask me if its safe for women to travel alone in the world.Â  for most of my life i've smiled and just said yesâ€”look at me, i'm here and i travel alone and i love it and i'll never stop and lets go!Â  but the older i get, the less this answer satisfies me.Â  its a true answer, but not true enough. .

over the last few years i've had a lot of conversations with women about travel and gender.Â  what i've learned is something i had always felt, but never fully considered:  that almost every woman i know is afraid, on some level, to move independently in the world, because of their gender.Â  for many women, that fear prevents them from walking alone, cycling alone, or traveling alone, specifically because of the risk of harassment and assault by men.Â  when you consider the implications of thisâ€”that an entire group of people is restricted from independent movement in the world, based on a fear of violence against themâ€”it makes this issue seem pretty important. link in bio.
.
photo by mathew moreno, 2011.Â  cycling across colombia, hugging baby goats.
.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: over the last several weeks, actually a year or so, we have seen a lot of commentary coming from both men and women on social media about how they simply don't believe the girls and women who have come forward about being sexually abused or assaulted. the vitriol in some of the comments has been bone chilling and down right mean. and, while we are well aware of each person's right to their opinion, we would like to submit to these individuals who've been so vocal with their opinions, that it is extremely possible that you have a child, family member, or close friend who is being or has been sexually abused or assaulted and they will never tell you! why? because they are positive that you won't believe them based on the way you've responded to other girl's and women's disclosure. everytime you get behind your keyboard and start blaming, shaming, and questioning other victims, you send a clear message to all victims that boldly exclaims "i don't believe you either!" whether that is completely true isn't the point because that's how your words are interpreted by those victims you know and the ones you don't. so, while we don't aim to strip anyone of their right to free speech, we would offer to you that there is a cost for freedom and the price you pay in this scenario is your child, family member, or close friend will not trust you with their truth and they just may continue to suffer in silence. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #mlk

text:
#chrisbrown has been detained in #paris on suspicion of rape, judicial sources confirmed to cbs news on tuesday. police sources told the associated press and reuters that the singer was detained with two other people and remained in custody in paris after a woman filed a rape complaint. 
one police official told the ap that the complaint was filed with police in the 17th arrondissement of northwest paris. the official said one of the others detained was brown's bodyguard. brown was detained monday and was still in custody tuesday while police study the complaint. 
in addition to the allegation of aggravated rape, brown is also facing possible charges for drug related offenses, the judicial sources told cbs news on tuesday.

the arrest was first reported by closer magazine, which has said a 24-year-old woman claims she was raped at brown's hotel suite on january 15. brown has been spotted over the last week in paris attending events around paris fashion week.

brown's publicists at sony music would not immediately comment. 
via. @artemusgordon #metoo #themfirst #freebillcosby #billcosby #michaeljackson #rkelly #firstthem

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
hey guys, everyone has a story. if u want to know more about me, hereâ€˜s mine being an #artphotographer :
i had a very close relationship to my grandfather, who was an amazing #photographer. in lack of children books, he used to read little me from books about the theory of #photography . time passed and so did he. i studied media and communication, used to live in france for studies, berlin worked for a big record label, usa worked for a renomated photographer and london where i used to work for nbc. but photography and #art never left me and after putting only a few #pictures online back then during my studies everything went very quickly as local institutions immediately wanted me to work for them. within only 4 years i had even photographed for international labels and also my personal dream had come true, fashion weeks being only 25. then came the â€lottery jackpotâ€œ, i was even talent scouted by andrÃ© leon-talley himself and encouraged to go to #vogue new york. a girls dream come true and i litterally lived the â€the devil wears pradaâ€œ story. so it was either go to ny for the big career on the fast lane of life or stay home in germany and finally marry my big love and become a devoted #mother eventually. well, you see the photo and my decision. sometimes it takes more #courage not to do things instead of doing them. the good thing though is that i managed to get financially #independent from photography to finally live my personal #dream and being able to carefully chose the collaborations to avoid further #metoo situations which unfortunately were quite often back then. i donâ€™t know, apparently something gets triggered when a man sees a petite former #dancer with a big #camera #lense in her handsğŸ™ŠğŸ™ˆğŸ˜…. also my decision allows me now to focus more on personal #creativity. so here i am and slowly finding my way back, being a mother and only #collaborating very selectively and #exclusively, on a tfp basis. lets see where the #journey is going. going back to my origins and my grandfatherâ€˜s advice. only do what makes you happy. rest in peace ğŸ’•

sexualness is what youâ€™re being, not doing. itâ€™s the nurturing, caring, expansive, joyful, creative, healing and orgasmic energy of living and the ultimate capacity to receive. sexualness is what youâ€™re looking for. 
being willing to receive sexual energy from someone does not mean you actually have to copulate with them! is it time to embrace your sexualness and start receiving you?

as you move up, your frequency expands & your experiences become closer to joy.

energy vampires have childhood wounds they suffer from & use adult relationships to play them out under the farce of a real relationship. they are 100% of the time a victim & unable to own their toxic behaviors. you can look & see a pattern of dysfunctional behavior & people close to them suffering from mental illness or suicide as a way to cope with abuse. people die from this- trust me. so please, if you are in the process of working & raising your vibration, look at toxic people in your life. if you are left constantly feeling sad or confused after engaging you need to realize who they are & save yourself. blood, bone, doesnâ€™t matter. these people donâ€™t want to be healed. they are unable to see the destructive damage they are causing themselves & others. save yourself.

text:
chris brown is currently being detained in paris. 
last night, a report surfaced indicating that chris brown has been arrested in paris, on the basis of a possible rape charge. early this morning, tmz has seemingly confirmed the validity of the claims. according to â€œfrench authorities,â€ brown has been detained and is currently in the midst of being processed for arrest. the charges, aggravated rape and narcotics offenses, stemmed after a woman accused the singer of raping her at the mandarin oriental hotel, after they met at le crystal nightclub.

the publication has since updated the story, confirming that chris brown has â€œeffectively been arrested.â€ part of his fate will be decided in the next two days, where heâ€™ll either have to be released or head to court. apparently, a prosecutor can request that brown be kept in custody, otherwise, the judge may decide to let him free, albeit with â€œobligations.â€ yet either option bodes ill for brown. said obligations will likely include surrendering his passport to french authorities, and remaining in paris until the trial kicks off, which may take up to one year. not to mention, brown will be required to make bi-weekly visits to french police stations to prove his presence.

this story continues to develop. for all intents and purposes, brown appears to be facing increasingly serious consequences.  keep up with the story at www.itskenbarbie.com#chrisbrown #chrisbrownbreezy #chrisbrownofficial #chrisbrownconcert #breezy #chrisbreezy #undecided #undecidedchallenge #metoo #entertainment #entertainmentnews #entertainmentblog #gossip #hboafm #indigo

text:
this is an entirely different story than alcohol but in reality it is the same, it's all addiction. 
to me it's infuriating that the message is that "nothing can be done". how is this possible? 
we have already know that limited advertising and marketing of cigarettes reduced the number of deaths from smoking since the surgeon general warning in 1964. we know by telling the truth and giving people information they did, in time, change the way society views smoking cigarettes. 
we can utilize the exact same approach for all the addictive substances we are being sold daily.  additionally treatment does work when given earlier in the progression of the issue. we need to end the stigma attached to alcoholics and substance abuse in our country so more people get access to the proper treatment. 
this message that there is nothing we can do is keeping us all sick and addicted and the companies that sell these items are laughing all the way to the bank. they have no incentive to change. 
the most important skill in the future will be management of addictions and it would make sense to start teaching children now about how to learn why they are craving this escape and what it means and how to get back in balance and reduce stress naturally. 
traditional western medication and talk therapy approach isn't working for the vast majority of people. we need major improvement in the way we treat addiction by using movement based therapy and holistic therapies that actually bring our body in balance and our cravings for unhealthy foods, drugs and alcohol and sugar go away on their own. 
it's so upsetting that we are allowing these corporations to make money off our addictions and aren't required to provide retribution or treatment for addiction. we have to be smarter than this and understand that there is no protection for the consumer and we all should be involved in actively fighting addiction in ourselves and our children as it's everywhere and will get worse unless we change. 
#addictionrecovery #onedayatatime #recoveroutloud #sober #weightlossjourney #empoweringwomen #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #transformation

text:
3/5 stars.

this quirky workplace satire was written in 2009, but feels especially relevant in the #metoo era.

joe is a failed salesman with a lot of weird sexual fantasies. lo and behold, one day he has an idea to transform one of his fantasies into a controversial solution for combatting sexual harassment in the workplace: he calls them â€œlightning rods,â€ and theyâ€™re women who are hired to provide sexual release for the most important male employees, the logic being that the men can now perform better at work and the company wonâ€™t have to worry about pesky lawsuits.

clearly this is an outrageous concept, and thatâ€™s definitely the whole point. the thing is, it takes off, and joe becomes wildly successful. this is a book that makes you cringe, as does most satire that seems all too plausible. 
dewittâ€™s writing is fresh and hilarious, reminding me at times of george saunders and david foster wallace. her use of the omniscient narrator is perfect for really highlighting joeâ€™s strangeness and the absurdity of the whole plot.

if i were judging this on the prose and characters alone, i would rate it higher, but unfortunately the plot itself does become rather redundant as we follow joe making improvements and new iterations of the lighting rod proposal.

iâ€™m grateful that this book introduced me to dewitt, whose writing i will definitely continue to seek out.

text:
how did i get so lucky?
â– 
â–  (cw: sexual violence, but i swear the message is uplifting).
â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
i just got through the 6 year anniversary of getting kidnapped and my life blowing up. trauma anniversaries generally reverberate through my body for weeks. i sailed through this one like it was just a normal day. what a goddamn gift. thanks, world.
â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
life always has struggle and i can be good with that. â™¡
â™¡
that said, the struggles for the past long time have felt epic and have required a kind of superstrength on my part, that has challenged me on every level. â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
just a few years ago i was weeping onto my mum's shoulder, wishing i had never been born, hoping i'd get hit by a bus asap.
â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
with a lot of work, and a whole lot of love, and a massive will to live,  i have been nursed back to humanity. i'm all soft and squishy inside. i can see a future for myself.  i feel blessed to have the privilege of accessing life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness. i get to love. â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
and as much as ive been robbed of my time and innocence by the men who raped me, i know that i know love better than they ever will. i can sleep well at night knowing i would never hurt someone in the way they hurt me.  i'm not perfect, but their degradation doesn't equate to me being lesser.
â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
or you, survivor frends. your perps behaviour is indicative of their pain and deficiency of heart and ethics. it says nothing about you, except your strength via surviving their failures. â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
everyone's path to recovery is different, but i am living proof that it is possible to be raped, beaten and robbed of ones humanity at a tender age, and to still recover a beautiful life. â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
 it is slow. it takes patience. it takes love. it takes generosity from the community. it takes a lot, but it isn't impossible. and survivors: please remember, the long road of struggle is not your fault despite it being your responsibility to heal. i believe in you. â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
â™¡
love you, folks.

text:
7 life logics: ğŸ™
1. make peace with your past....so it doesn't spoil your present.
2. what others think of you is....none of your business.
3. time heals almost everything....give the time, some time.
4. no one is the reason of your happiness....except you yourself.
5. don't compare your life with others....you have no idea what their journey is all about.
6. stop thinking too much....it's alright not to know all the answers.
7. smile....you don't own all the problems in the world.

6. stop thinking too much....it is alright not to know all the answers.
7. smile....you do not own all the problems in the world.

text:
â€œbeginning on jan. 22, visitors to gracie mansion will encounter a disconsolate sight as they approach the residence of the mayor of new york city and his family: a cloaked, faceless figure sitting on the ground behind its own severed feet, a signal that an unusual set of guests has arrived.  they were invited by the first lady.  the figure, made of dark bronze, is a sculpture by the artist #karawalker, titled â€œinvasive species (to be placed in your native garden),â€ and has been put on a small patch of land near the entrance.  the occasion is â€œshe persists: a century of women artists in new york,â€ an installation of works by 44 artists and collectives in the public spaces of #graciemansion. the show is the largest one to be mounted there and the first to focus exclusively on female and women-identified creators, all of whom have significant connections to new york city.â€ -- jillian steinhauer for the new york times (@nytimes), jan 20, 2019.  exhibition curated by #jessicabellbrown. â€œâ€™this exhibit is really important at this time, given the #metoo movement, the centennial anniversary of the suffrage movement, the historic number of women running for office,â€™ the cityâ€™s first lady, chirlane mccray, said in an interview at the mansion. â€œand of course, the personal is the political. what i believe is being exercised in my home as well as out there in the world.â€ public tours begin february 4th through december.

text:
martha graham (may 11, 1894 â€“ april 1, 1991) was an american modern dancer and choreographer.
her style, the graham technique, reshaped american dance and is still taught worldwide.
she danced and taught for over seventy years.
graham was the first dancer to perform at the white house, travel abroad as a cultural ambassador, and receive the highest civilian award of the us: the presidential medal of freedom with distinction.
in her lifetime she received honors ranging from the key to the city of paris to japan's imperial order of the precious crown.
she said, in the 1994 documentary the dancer revealed, "i have spent all my life with dance and being a dancer.
it's permitting life to use you in a very intense way.
sometimes it is not pleasant.
sometimes it is fearful.
but nevertheless it is inevitable." graham has been sometimes termed the "picasso of dance".

text:
fantastic day yesterday at the "33rd annual brooklyn tribute to dr. martin luther king, jr.," at @bam_brooklyn. this was my first time.

i'm a huge fan of "the brian lehrer show" on wnyc, and i always used to go to the annual celebration he held at the brooklyn museum. then they moved it to the apollo. i went uptown once.

i had originally planned to go to bam for their free mlk day screening of "dolores," about the bad*ss chicana activist and community organizer,  dolores de la huerta. i heard her on a radio interview a few years ago, and i was smitten. 
then the larger, overall, bam celebration, starting 10:30 a.m. caught my eye. the keynote was going to be #metoo founder, tarana burke. "dolores" was at 1:00 p.m. i decided to do both.

there were musical performances by an interdenominational choir, and hip hop artist, odyssey (think i heard of him before--he has an anderson paak vibe). and it was a progessive political love fest with all the favorites: cumbo, jeffries, schumer, clarke, johnson, de blasio himself and nyc first lady mccray.

not enough space to cover all tarana burke spoke about, but here are some gems from her, as well as from civil rights peers of dr. king who trained her:
*things happen when they're supposed to.
*trauma halts possibility, but movement activates it.
*real vision for change should take your breath away.
* when dealt with opposition, say: i will not violate your dignity, but i will not compromise mine. the decisions i make will benefit everyone--even my enemies.
*awareness in and of itself is not a virtue, unless it's fueled by a moral imperative.

one running theme between burke and delores is the way that women are not given their due as architects and strategists of major movements, and great things. she co-founded the united farm workers union, and helped orchestrate its famous national grape boycott, but her dear friend, cesar chavez, is given all the credit. but here's where she did get credit: when president obama bestowed her the presidential medal of freedom, he acknowledged that his translation of a phrase she created, "si se puede!" is where he got "yes we can!" see this documentary! and take a young person with you.
name: Petra E. Lewis

text:
this book explores a time in the life of tise, a young and beautiful girl, her love for modelling and her near death experience. it talks about the strained relationship between tise and her mum and how no matter how much tise strived to please her mum, she never seemed to do enough. it also explores friendship in its pure state between tise and her friend chichi. ''not all heroes wear capes,'' but this wasn't revealed till the book's end. it also addressed other topics that are not freely discussed but is beginning to gain attention in the african and nigerian society, topics like depression and suicide.

text:
did you know that your first minutes after waking determine how the rest of your day will go? scientists have proven that reaching for our phones, checking texts, scrolling social media, or even thinking thoughts of dread for the new day or allowing toxic feelings in can actually make your serotonin levels drop and severely reduce your quality of living. love yourself enough to start out right with things that feed your soul before your feet hit the floor. i lived with chronic depression and anxiety since i was 5, and i full well know what itâ€™s like to not be able to make it out of bed. changing my thoughts changed my brain chemical production, and thereby my world. and i needed the right medication to even be able to maintain my thoughts or even think about praying, meditating, reading, or going to work and taking a shower. it took time and a lot of hard work, and i definitely still have down days. but now i know that a down day is not the equivalent of a down life, nor is it a portent into a future of depression. nor does it make me panic, because i retrained my mind to talk myself through whatever my state of mind is so that i can get out of bed and flood my body with a day of high nutrients in the form of safe and healthy relationships, healthy and organic supplements, and things my heart needs like creating, writing, thrift shop-hopping with a friend or road-tripping by myself listening to some recording artists i tagged in the picture above. i believe firmly in the power of speaking affirmations over myself and writing out any toxic thoughts as soon as they come up to give to god so that my mind, body, soul, bloodstream, and spirit donâ€™t suffer needlessly. whatâ€™s your way of loving yourself first?
#mercysisters #shefoundmercy #runformercy5k
