text:
yes to all the sisters i walked alongside during the los angeles womenâ€™s march.

it was overwhelming to feel the collective resistance and refusal to accept the suppression (i donâ€™t use that term lightly) of womenâ€™s rights in the usa that is getting worse with every new piece of legislation d.trump is passing.

heâ€™s making getting a safe abortion harder, getting contraception harder, getting paid the same as men, harder. undeniable facts, not opinion, not fake news. heâ€™s aggressively ensured a man who attacked a young woman now sits on the us supreme court. all the while the president himself has been accused of sexual assault by 17 women and counting, yet heâ€™s still sitting up there in his ivory tower.

iâ€™m angry on behalf of my american sisters, iâ€™m angry because of the impact this vile humanâ€™s bigoted beliefs are having on the rest of the entire planet. if you support trump and/or donâ€™t believe in feminism, you donâ€™t believe in the safety of women, so either move on along, or preferably, stick around and some reading on behalf of your mother, sister, wife, daughter.

#impeachtrump #ibelieveher #metoo #womensmarch

think about the last time you felt most confident. where were you, who were you with, what just happened or is happening in your life? â €
â €
i would say most, if not all, of us feel more empowered to do things outside of our comfort zone when we know we are not alone. â €
â €
think about it in your social life, i know for myself i would be way more likely to go up and introduce myself to a guy at a bar when i'm out with friends than alone. â €
â €
it's same for business and your career. when you feel supported you are more empowered to speak up, stand up and act on the things you want in life. â €
â €
that's something the #metoo movement did for all of us. it brought women together. it showed one another that we are not alone and we can speak our mind. â €
â €
that's why for wex, one of our core values is community- our whole movement grew from community. â €
â €
it is all of us, together, that will empower one another to achieve our dreams. â €

gabriela portland showed up in solidarity with two events over the weekend: we marched with the #metoo speak out and womenâ€™s march because women everywhere must be liberated from patriarchy rooted in capitalism and imperialism, and to recognize a movement that must fight for our indigenous, black, brown, and lgbtq siblings. the following day our members marched in the @ilpsportland contingent in the reclaim mlk march, organized by @dontshootpdx. we joined ranks united against police brutality and militarism, to honor the legacy of mlk jr, and to lift up black lives who must be free from the racist and violent system of us imperialism. we are inspired to follow in the path of the youth and black womxn who lead us. 
#metoo #blacklivesmatter #riseresistunite #slayimpe

come ogni anno, l'annuncio delle candidature si lascia dietro polemiche per gli snobbati (nessuna donna Ã¨ in lizza per la miglior regia, con buona pace del movimento #metoo) ma anche reazioni di sgomento per gli outsider che ce l'hanno fatta.

vediamo quali sono le curiositÃ  riguardo alle scelte dell'academy di questa edizione:
ã€°ï¸ per la prima volta due registi stranieri si sfidano nella categoria miglior regia per le rispettive pellicole in bianco e nero, vale a dire alfonso cuarÃ³n per "roma" (messico) e padel pawlikowski per "cold war" (polonia). se contiamo anche yorgos lanthimos, questa Ã¨ la cinquina piÃ¹ internazionale dell'anno.
ã€°ï¸ e a proposito de "la favorita", su 10 nominations ottenute ben 3 sono per il suo cast esclusivamente femminile, divenendo il 19esimo film nella storia a raggiungere tale traguardo.
ã€°ï¸ grazie al ruolo di ally in "a star is born", lady gaga diviene la prima artista femminile della storia a venir candidata nello stesso anno come migliore attrice protagonista e come autrice della miglior canzone (barbra streisand ci riuscÃ¬ ma in anni differenti).
ã€°ï¸ impensabile fino a un anno fa, "black panther" diviene il primo film tratto da un fumetto a essere nominato come miglior film.

ã€°ï¸ boom dei film candidati con al loro interno una vasta rappresentazione di personaggi lgbt, a cominciare da "la favorita", passando ovviamente per "bohemian rhapsody", fino a "green book" e "a star is born", senza dimenticare "copia originale".
ã€°ï¸ le grandi escluse di questa edizione sono emily blunt e nicole kidman. entrambe avevano non uno ma ben due ruoli di prestigio con cui potevano gareggiare sia come migliore attrice protagonista che non protagonista: la prima con "mary poppins returns" e "a quiet place", la seconda con "destroyer" e "boy erased" (ancora inediti in italia).

text:
when i say i hate my chest people always laugh, and quickly follow with "i wish i had tits that big!" or the inevitable "well, i love your boobs!" these comments have varied between light-hearted banter as a way to make me feel better to full on harassment (and unfortunately sometimes assault). there has never been a moment i have been proud of them. they hurt my back, they make everything i wear look awkward or far more provocative than intended, they get in the way, they make people feel free to invalidate my gender identity, and they will likely cause my spine to deteriorate (like they did my great grandmother and are starting to do to her daughter, my grandma) unless i one day have the means to get a reduction. when i say i hate them, i truly mean i hate them.

but... for the first time in my life i feel okay about that area of my body. i looked in the mirror as i was getting dressed this morning and didn't get upset or depressed. i was happy. my tattoo diverts people's attention from an area that has been the bane of my existence since i was 9 years old. it makes me feel like i have some sort of control over my body. 
don't tell me body modification can't make a massive positive impact on your life. take steps to become the person you are supposed to be, wether it is through tottoos, piercings, or simply seeking help and cutting toxicity out of your life. if i can work on this shit and make progress, i know beyond a shadow of a doubt you can too. i have faith in you, i love you, and you are worthy of the life you want.

text:
domestic violence laws in california do not protect stepparents!

total and completely twisted lie. itâ€™s shocking debbie would take it this far after 23 years of friendship. so debbie believes and has spread lies to the #lajolla community and all our mutual friends a narrative as follows:

.
.

text:
last september, on a train ride between d.c. and baltimore i began, for the first time, writing down my experience of assault while studying abroad in italy 2013 and my rape, which happened exactly a year prior. before that moment, i was riddled with fear every time i considered writing down what had happened. even the idea of sitting down and writing made it feel too real. it was only while trying to figure out how i could connect food (in this case ice cream) with a story of â€œselfâ€ for @grlsquashâ€™s second issue that the stories came out effortlessly. along with my experience, i paired the narrative of artemisia gentileschi and the tale of her most well-known subject, judith.
â€¢
here is a snippet of gentileschiâ€™s story that i wrote from the latest issue of @grlsquash. order a copy with the link in my bio.
â€¢
â€œ405 years before #metoo took over online, 405 years before mario batali and ken freidman were accused of assault, 405 years before i was raped, artemisia gentileschi, a italian baroque painter, was raped by her tutor, agostino tassi. today, gentileschi is known equally for her powerful paintings and the seven-month trail in which gentileschi was tasked with proving her rape. 
neither rape nor her talents as a woman artist were rare in 15th century rome. the fact that there was a trial and that gentileschi became a well-known artist was...â€

at least, have some good graffiti skills and some respect for others if you stand for the metoo movement. ğŸ–#badgraffiti #metoo

text:
project reflecting on a woman's wish to be seen and her simultaneous impulse to hide herself, after centuries of misogynistic programming.

for centuries, women have been reduced solely to their appearance, their physical beauty deemed their only worth. western philosophers who have shaped our collective thinking -Â aristotle[i], socrates[ii], jean-jacques rousseau[iii], darwin[iv], schopenhauer[v], nietzsche[vi] -Â compared women to animals, incapable of rational thought, devoid of intelligence. and although present generations are desperately trying to escape these narrow confinements, the ingrained programming leaves many women struggling with their self-worth.

the objectification of the female body is an effective form of dehumanization. women's sexuality is exploited and suppressed at the same time. admired and reviled, chased and judged, praised and ridiculed.Â this opppresive societal schizophrenia is mirrored in every woman's soul.

this series reflects on the desire to be seen, coupled with the shame and instinctive need to hide.

text:
kids say the craziest things, right? i know in my experience with kids, they love to make up words, people, stories, you name it! most recently, i was discussing animals with a little boy i was caring for and asked "so what do chickens make?", thinking he would reply with eggs. instead he replied, "chicken nuggets!" ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ he wasn't wrong!! haha
.
what about when they say no? is that so crazy?
.
now before you go and think i'm saying to let your kids talk back, hear me out! in today's age of #metoo and consent being a "hot topic", teaching your kid to be able to assert themselves to say no is really a healthy thing to do.
.
this week on the blog, i give you a few practical guidelines to help teach your child about how consent is so important and it can be taught in little moments each day!
.
click the #linkinbio for the full post!
.
what's the craziest thing you ever heard your child (or any child!) say? let me know!!
.
.

text:
today vs this time last year. 
i've missed 3 of the 10 days i've allotted myself to miss the gym this year due to being sick. also haven't been super healthy but also haven't been over indulging either. 
in the first picture i'm wearing my pink tank top today, and in one later on you see the same one in my work mirror where i look smaller. i'm not. it's that i've ate today and i'm bloated thanks to mother nature. i'm working on getting used to noticing it because 75 percent of the time when i feel bloated is when i'm the most convinced i have made no progress at all. 
also still going to deep condition and treat the damage i've done to the top part of my hair. underneath isn't as damaged because i didn't lighten it twice in a row like i had the top. so far it's going great and i'm sticking to the paraban free 7 in 1 miracle treatment from #aussie.

i'm super proud lately. i'm proud for setting goals. i'm proud for sticking to them. and i'm overly confident that this motivation will stick this year. 
what i sometimes forget is to tell everyone why i started this journey;

november 2017 after several emotionally, mentally and physically abusive relationships, and having already been diagnosed with depression, anxiety and borderline personality disorder (bpd) i was done. i genuinely was done, and with the help of my best friend and my family i admitted myself to the treatment facility at st. joseph mercy hospital of ann arbor. i was 26 years old, feeling like a failure, not feeling like i was myself or motivated to thinks for me. i stayed there for 9 days, but it was while there i met someone else who has become another good friend, and bridged me to a new social circle of very supportive individuals.

i started spending all of my time with them for the most part and eventually moved in with them,and my boyfriend. in this, i decided everything i did had to be with the intention for myself. it had to hold my best interest at heart and it had to help me get where i wanted to be. one of those issues being how i viewed myself. my weight was a big sore spot for my depression, and for my self esteem. i was convinced i wasn't worth anything because of it.

text:
it's so sad, it's very true that women aren't being treated at the same rate as men and when in treatment are virtually unsupported by their families and friends. 
when in treatment i observed many men with families and wives helping them through this painful situation and attended therapy and were committed to their husbands and supported their sobriety. 
for women there was a sharp contrast, no one's husbands were there because women aren't supported in any illness and addiction is no different.  women had their children taken away, their families and friends abandoned them and all of them had been victims of domestic violence and sexual assault. 
when women get addicted to drugs and alcohol they are judged more harshly than men so they don't get help. they are always the caregivers for others and are left alone when they need support. 
my ex h abused me and then threw me out when he decided that i was too fat and disgusting to love and told my parents i was the problem because of my excessive drinking.  he never stopped to think perhaps his abuse was what i was escaping from? it's so typical that women are abused and then turn to alcohol and are abandoned when they need support and love the most. 
my own experience with it is that my brother is looked at like a great example of sobriety while i should just shut up about it. people insist that i wasn't as bad, that i didn't need the help and i overreacted. as usual anything a man does is amazing but when i do it there is nothing to be proud of, nothing special or anything. the reaction is bizarre and sad and makes no sense to me. 
link in bio!

#drydiet #sober #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #transformation #truthinwellness #liveyourtruth #soberyogi #transformation #empoweringwomen
